node.text: A few months ago @aliceaedy and I started working on a film about the loneliness epidemic amongst young people in the UK. We set up an answer phone where young people across the country could leave anonymous voicemails talking about their experiences. We received over 6 hours of voice messages. The responses were honest, articulate and moving. What surprised us most was the constant theme of being surrounded by people, but still feeling alone. So many of us feel lonely, despite being more ‚Äòconnected‚Äô than ever before. The result is a 15 minute film called ‚ÄòDisconnected'. We used actors to build abstract dramatisations recorded on 16mm and filmed in Blackpool, that play against the audio of these real testimonies. The film is directed by Alice and is her first ever short film!! Last weekend we had a chance to screen it to our closest friends and family and we were overjoyed to receive so many positive responses. We‚Äôre currently in the process of submitting to festivals and hope to share it online within the next year. If you submitted a voicemail to this project and want to get in touch you can email me at hello@jacksgap.com
Forever pretending to be normal... sometimes it just slips out. ü§™

We did it! Today we joined @extinctionrebellion and thousands of activists from across the country as we took control of five bridges in central London. It was the greatest act of mass civil disobedience in this country for decades. Whilst todays events may have inconvenienced some people, it is nothing compared to the challenges that threaten our future. We are at a breaking point. For far too long governments have avoided action on climate change by banking on the fact that young people don‚Äôt understand the issues. We stood in solidarity today to make it clear that we understand what is happening, that we are scared for our future and we won‚Äôt stand by and be passive citizens anymore.

node.text: Yesterday I spoke to the @guardian about why I‚Äôm backing @extinctionrebellion. This week I‚Äôve been involved in various direct actions in the build up to a day of mass civil disobedience this Saturday in London. Just this month the UN announced we have 12 years to limit climate catastrophe, yet our government are simply ignoring the problem. Our future is under threat because of things we haven‚Äôt even had a hand in. We should be angry. We should make our voices heard. As George Monbiot wrote earlier this week 'Do not allow those who have caused this crisis to define the limits of political action. Do not allow those whose magical thinking got us into this mess to tell us what can and cannot be done.‚Äô History tells us that direct action works. That‚Äôs why I‚Äôll be joining Extinction Rebellion in London this Saturday. It‚Äôs no exaggeration to say that to care about climate change is to care about the future of humanity. I hope you‚Äôll join me. ‚úäüèºüåç

Yesterday I had the opportunity to talk about three trips that have shaped the way I look at the environment and the issue of climate change at @britishfilminstitute for @vevolution_ . Despite spending months preparing the talk and learning it by heart, it didn‚Äôt go as well as I had hoped. I forgot a few lines and had a few technical hitches. Nothing major but I guess that‚Äôs the risk of public speaking. It‚Äôs a humbling reminder that things don‚Äôt always go to plan and sometimes you just have to roll with the punches. This week I joined @extinctionrebellion to deliver a message to Theresa May at Downing Street. We are everyday citizens who are afraid for our future. Climate change poses a devastating threat to all life on on earth yet our government are too busy squabbling over Brexit. Whilst we must all make changes in our individual lives it is up to our government to create policy and a framework that puts planet over profit. We need a political leaders who will tax carbon emissions, ban fracking, cut subsidies to polluting industries, prohibit single use plastics and invest heavily in renewable energy. We are the next generation and it‚Äôs up to us to take up the fight. Join me in making our voices heard on the 17th of November. üåç‚úäüèº Film by @lizziegilson1313

Like many others, my passion for the natural world was inspired by growing up watching David Attenborough's programs like Planet Earth and Blue planet. This show is on a whole other level. Voiced by Sir David Attenborough and shot across every content on earth using the latest technology, ‚ÄòOur Planet‚Äô took over 4 years to make. 
I recently had the opportunity to travel to Kenya with @wwf_uk and @netflix to go behind the scenes and see first hand how they film some of the episodes. I can‚Äôt wait to share some footage with you. ‚ÄòOur Planet drops on Netflix on the 5th of April!

It was an honour to be a part of the launch of @netflix new series ‚ÄòOur Planet‚Äô last night. This breathtaking collaboration between @wwf_uk and Silverback Films tells the story of our beautiful planet, but also explores the devastating impact us humans are having. 
It was an inspiring evening including talks by the renowned climate scientist Johan Rockstrom, Sir David Attenborough and the team at Silverback Films. 
It fills me with hope to see these issues being discussed on the big screen. In order to take action, we must first understand the problems we face and this show, voiced by Sir David Attenborough goes along way towards telling that story. It drops on Netflix on the 5th of April! üåç

This morning we went to Downing Street with @extinctionrebellion to present Theresa May with a Declaration of Rebellion. Climate change is a threat so urgent that it requires radical activism: for people to be brave, to draw attention to the issue and to put pressure on politicians to protect our future. So much of the most important social change has come through direct action & peaceful protest. ‚úäüèª Our government's abject failure to protect citizens and the next generations from unimaginable suffering brought about by climate breakdown and social collapse is no longer tolerable. We believe it is our duty as citizens to rebel using peaceful civil disobedience when faced with criminal inactivity by its Government. The recent budget didn‚Äôt even mention climate change - that is unacceptable. We want no fracking, no coal, to tax emissions; a zero carbon economy by 2025.

It felt so empowering to be part of direct action this morning. We can‚Äôt wait to be part of Rebellion Day next Saturday 17th November and if you feel passionate about this we really hope you will join us. Enough is enough ‚úäüèª‚úäüèª‚úäüèª

The last year has been a wake up call. The #metoo campaign has highlighted the endemic ‚Äòtoxic masculinity‚Äô in our society.

Why do we men act this way? I can‚Äôt help feel it comes from a place of fear and insecurity. Fear to show love and be loved. Fear to embrace emotion and be vulnerable.

If we want to create a more equal society it starts with us men accepting ourselves and understanding our own inherant gender privilege.

Patriarchal privilege, may seem invisible to us but that‚Äôs only because it a system that we‚Äôve benefitted from since birth.

I‚Äôm grateful to have been raised by a strong mother who taught me the power of women and encouraged me to embrace my own weaknesses and vulnerability.

Ahead of this years UN General Assembly debate we can all do more to be outspoken allies and remember that ultimately, we were all brought into this world by a woman.

We have been overwhelmed to receive the most articulate, insightful and heartfelt testimonies about loneliness in Britain today. Our inbox was full within a matter of hours of sharing the post. We‚Äôve now logged and cleared all entries, so if you feel compelled to call, please do so.

I am so deeply passionate about bringing awareness to this topic and these messages are the bedrock of this project. I would like to extend a huge thanks to everyone who felt brave enough to call and beat the stigma around loneliness. Together we can use our voices to create a new narrative.

We want to know, do you feel lonely? Why? Are you able to talk about it? If not, why not? Do you think there is a taboo surrounding the issue? Perhaps you have ideas for solutions? What can we do to feel less lonely? Why is it such a prevalent issue today?

These submissions will contribute to a documentary about loneliness. Loneliness is a silent and invisible epidemic affecting millions of us. While social media provides the tools for us to in theory be more ‚Äòconnected' than ever, many of us feel completely alone.

Britain is the loneliness capital of Europe. With 9 million people reported to have experienced some form of loneliness in 2017, this year the government appointed a ‚ÄòMinister of Loneliness‚Äô. In the UK, it is one of the last remaining taboos. While conversations about mental health, anxiety, depression, have progressed in recent years, few of us admit to feeling lonely. However, loneliness is often a contributing factor to these issues.

This short film offers a chance to start a conversation around the issue. We have set up an answer phone where you can leave anonymous voicemails about your personal experiences with loneliness.

Please note, UK entries only. You will NOT be contacted but your submission may be used anonymously in the documentary.

Hey friends, it‚Äôs a new year which means a new you! I‚Äôd like to share something with you that I‚Äôm personally very passionate about. To keep a long story short, two and a half years ago I stopped eating meat and adopted a plant based diet. At first it took some getting used to and along the way i‚Äôve had moments of doubt and deviation. I‚Äôve often refrained from talking about it, aware of the stereotypical reputation of the self-righteous and dogmatic vegan. I never wanted to be ‚Äòthat guy‚Äô. But today, right at this moment I feel physically fitter, significantly healthier and undoubtedly happier than I ever have before. It is single handedly the best decision I‚Äôve ever made and I know with certainty that I will never go back. It has deepened my understanding of food and improved my relationship with what I eat too. What‚Äôs more, it turns out that adopting a plant based diet is possibly the single most effective thing you can do to help the environment and also to support animal rights. To me it feels like a no brainer. I wake up everyday feeling as though I have gained something great. The plant based movement is an exciting one full of inspiring and ambitious people and it‚Äôs growing dramatically every year. If you feel like trying something new this year, or you‚Äôre just curious to learn more check out @weareveganuary. It‚Äôs an amazing scheme that will support you with information and advice across the month of January. To me adopting a plant based diet was about informing myself and there‚Äôs no better place to start than the veganuary site. Link in bio! Photo cred to @rosie_matheson. Earlier this year I travelled to Somaliland with Alice. I'm excited to share a series we worked on together. 'Somaliland's Nomads‚Äô is portrait series from Boodley, a remote village surviving the drought and hunger crisis in Somaliland. 
Somaliland could be considered the canary in the mine in a world that is getting hotter and where extreme weather conditions are becoming more common. Somaliland‚Äôs nomads are living on the front-lines of climate change, with the increasing frequency and ferocity of drought. It is an immediate life-or-death challenge that pushes their already precarious existence to the edge. 
For years now Somaliland has experienced extreme drought. However recently the drought has become increasingly severe, with thousands on the brink of starvation. This year the government of Somaliland declared a national emergency with more than 1.5 million people affected by the drought afflicting the state and 80% of it‚Äôs livestock wiped out. 18 million were affected across East Africa.

Taken in a portable studio, in this portrait series we have removed the subjects from their direct environment in order to challenge the cliched depictions from a region where news reports often focus on poverty and suffering. Photographing this way we intended to create a greater sense of connection with the subject and empathy on behalf of the viewer. 
Despite having had the least impact on the environment it is these nomads who suffer the most. By putting a human face on those on the front-lines of climate change and celebrating the individuals from this village and region in this way, we hope to draw attention to the increasing threat of climate change to the region. #facesofchange

Two nights ago I woke up to the sound of a helicopter circling above my home. Strangely this isn't an unusual occurrence where I live. So at first I thought nothing of it. A short while later two fire engines raced down the road outside. Still nothing too untoward... However as I lay in bed, curiosity got the better of me. I wondered if anyone else was hearing this. Perhaps they've tweeted? Gingerly, I typed the name of my street into twitter. I wasn't expecting anything, perhaps a fellow insomniac with an equal curiosity. The first search result was a grainy video showing a towering inferno looming out of the dark. The woman filming sound exasperated 'I've never seen anything like this before!' As I watched the 7 second clip over and over I gradually began to realise that this towering inferno was in fact the block of flats at the end of my road. I stumbled out of bed and opened my curtains and there it was. Silent from the distance but burning a bright orange in the night sky. - A plume of smoke billowing off the top. It must have been burning for around 20 minutes. I got dressed as quickly as I could, grabbed my camera and raced downstairs. Once outside the scene was horrific. Like something out of a Hollywood movie. The police were still in the process of creating a barrier and residents had began to gather. As we watched in shock a mother and son appeared shouting that they had family members on the upper floors. From the ground it was possible to see flash lights moving around. As more and more people gathered we watched, utterly helpless and distressed as flames engulfed the building. Amid the chaos and the confusion medics and police worked together to secure a permitter and look after the public whilst firefighters entered the building. It's in these sort of moments that you feel full of respect and admiration for the bravery involved in running towards a scenario like that rather than away from it. 200 firefighters battled the flames well into the early hours of the morning. So far it has been reported that 17 people have died. Another 17 are in critical condition and 37 being treated in hospital. To donate please see link in bio.

Two weeks ago, I was invited by my friends at @helprefugeesuk to visit a refugee camp in Calais, France, commonly known as 'The Jungle'. Over the last ten years The Jungle has developed and grown to become a well known holding ground for those fleeing worn torn countries and turbulent lives. The residents occupying these camps range in nationality and origin from countries like Syria, Sudan, Eritrea, Afghanistan, Egypt and the Kurdistan region of Iraq (amongst others). Their hope is to find freedom, liberation and a future in the United Kingdom. 
When we visited it was raining heavily and it was clear to see the infrastructure of the camp struggling under the strain of its community. As you can imagine the conditions were beyond basic. The ground on which it was build is considered toxic and too dangerous for construction by the French government. We witnessed over 5000 people living side by side, mostly in tents, wooden sheds and camper vans in bog like conditions. 
Two days after we visited the camp french authorities dismantled it and dispersed its residents. But this doesn‚Äôt mean the problem has been resolved‚Ä¶ The jungle is just a window into the plight of millions of people, who are on the move, living in limbo without a home or future, on the run from political unrest.

Later this month I'll be travelling again with @helprefugeesuk but this time to Greece, to visit a few of the military run refugee camps to try and understand what needs to be done in preparation for the long cold winter ahead. If it interests you check back, as i‚Äôll be sharing my journey here.

You think your food will be limited, you think you won't get the nutrition you need, you think you'll spend the rest of your life eating kale... But it so isn't like that. Through veganism I've become so much more excited about food and nutrition. I've also had the chance to travel around and find so many beautiful restaurants and wonderful people serving good wholesome food. Vegasim isn't just ethical, it's environmental. The agriculture industry as it stands today simply isn't sustainable. Vegasim also doesn't have to be expensive. Vegetables and fruit are cheaper than most meats! Everyone makes their own choice of diet. This is mine. I'm interested to know what are your thoughts on Veganism? Also if you're at all interested in Veganism take some time to watch Cowspiracy. It will blow your mind. This feast was provided by @primalroost here in England. A beautiful Paleo cafe started by a good friend of mine. ~ The Northern Lights - On our last night in Greenland our flight was diverted to the capital of Nuuk. We had been told there was a chance to seeing the Aurora Borealis during our time in Greenland but it was unlikely as it was early in the season. As we drove out of the airport and left the light pollution behind the sky light up bright green. It surged, danced and shimmered. It's one of the most magical things I've ever seen. We spent the rest of the night camped out on the end of he harbour watching the lights move over the water. I feel very lucky to have had a chance to see and photograph them. Thank you Greenland for such an amazing 8 days!!

I met this man during my travels in India. I passed him as he was trying to tie a bit of string around one arm to make a bracelet. He was using his teeth but was struggling and so I offered my assistance. He seemed pleased by this and once the bracelet was done he offered me a handful of nuts in return. We ended up sat in front of each other communicating in this strange way for a little while.  I was touched by the fact that we were able to connect through such a simple thing and despite the language barrier. Before I left I asked to take his portrait. This is the image I shot.
